Paradoxically, marriage can create emotional problems for polygamous families yet polygamy is considered an advantageous marital practice in many cultures. The objective of this study was twofold: (1) to re-examine the common perception that marital quality in polygynous unions is poor, and (2) to study how the practice of polygamy affects psychological well-being in an Arab community by taking into account emotional affairs and the dilemma over marital division of attention.

In Moroccan rural society, early marriage affects both the bride and the family. Although the mother's experiences are a limitation for her to build her own personality, she must continue to fulfill her social and cultural obligations. Three aspects are explored: the family structure, the adolescence period of the bride, and delinquency. This paper explores the experiences of a poor rural bride. It emphasizes that if the family agrees to the early marriage of their underage daughter, they also have to accept the domination of the groom's family, because they will provide support for the family decision.

The purpose of this paper is to examine and compare the experiences of divorce and the reconstruction of widowhood among Palestinians and Jews.
